question:

"{{subject}}, I want to work with you because... and I would want to work with you more if..."
subject: TJ Walker
value: TJ: I want to work with you because our flow, rhythm and chemistry continues to rock. It’s been such a treat to absorb so much of your git knowledge.  So I think I finally have some constructive criticism for you. Two sides of the same coin: on one hand, I continue to admire the way in which you speak your truth, seemingly fearlessly, and give others genuine feedback. In giving feedback, one holds the trust tension between truth and safety. And I think that there are instances in which some of your feedback might have the unintended consequence of making an individual feel unwanted, disliked, or not part of the group. I’m thinking about a few instances, one was your feedback on the posture of Jason, which might be a pretty personal / sensitive thing. I can’t speak to the experiences of our groupmates, and honestly, I think that our groupmates received your feedback very well. And, I want you to be aware of this tension, because I imagine that there will be instances in the future in which you’ll be giving constructive criticism to a team member who is not such a jedi at receiving feedback, and they’ll experience a super-ego attack and become disproportionately defensive and angry. So my suggestion: keep speaking your truth, and keep reading your audience so you are aware of potential barriers to an individual receiving the feedback you’re giving. <3
